  <section>
    <title>Outline of book</title>
    <para>
      The book has the following core elements:
      <itemizedlist>
        <listitem><para>
          <emphasis>UML for organizational modeling</emphasis> where we provide an introduction to
          the <emphasis>Unified Modeling Language</emphasis> used throughout the remainder of the
          book.
        </para></listitem>
        <listitem><para>
          <emphasis>business process design using URDAD</emphasis> which explains the URDAD
          methodology and shows how it can be applied to business process design.
        </para></listitem>
        <listitem><para>
          <emphasis>Implementation mappings</emphasis> which provides an overview of how the
          organizational architecture and business process designs are mapped onto a concrete
          implementation
        </para></listitem>
        <listitem><para>
          <emphasis>organizational architecture</emphasis> where we look at architectural patterns
          and strategies and how <emphasis>Capability Driven Architecture</emphasis> (CDA) can be
          used to define an organization's architecture by combining architectural patterns and
          strategies,
        </para></listitem>
        
      </itemizedlist>
    </para>
  </section>
  
  <section>
    <title>Using a model organization to illustrate the concepts</title>
    <para>
      Throughout the book the concepts are illustrated within a model organization. We have based
      the model organization on our company, <emphasis>Solms TCD</emphasis>.   Most of the concepts
      discussed in the examples are implemented as is within <emphasis>Solms TCD</emphasis>.
      However, at times, aspects of our model organization deviate from the actual realization within
      our company. These deviations are introduced to illustrate concepts we have not currently
      implemented, often because our current size does not yet justify it.
    </para>
  </section>
  
  
